eativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/ Open Access http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/ Background In breast magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), the differentiation between benign and malignant breast masses relies on the Breast Imaging Reporting and Data System Magnetic Resonance Imaging (BI-RADS-MRI) lexicon. While BI-RADS-MRI classification demonstrates high sensitivity, specificities vary. This study aimed to evaluate the feasibility of machine learning models utilizing radiomics features derived from synthetic MRI to distinguish benign from malignant breast masses. Methods Patients who underwent breast MRI, including a multi-dynamic multi-echo (MDME) sequence using 3.0 T MRI, and had histopathologically diagnosed enhanced breast mass lesions were retrospectively included. Clinical features, lesion shape features, texture features, and textural evaluation metrics were extracted. Machine learning models were trained and evaluated, and an ensemble model integrating BI-RADS and the machine learning model was also assessed. Results A total of 199 lesions (48 benign, 151 malignant) in 199 patients were included in the cross-validation dataset, while 43 lesions (15 benign, 28 malignant) in 40 new patients were included in the test dataset. For the test dataset, the sensitivity, specificity, accuracy, and area under the curve (AUC) of the receiver operating characteristic for BI-RADS were 100%, 33.3%, 76.7%, and 0.667, respectively. The logistic regression model yielded 64.3% sensitivity, 80.0% specificity, 69.8% accuracy, and an AUC of 0.707. The ensemble model achieved 82.1% sensitivity, 86.7% specificity, 83.7% accuracy, and an AUC of 0.883. The AUC of the ensemble model was significantly larger than that of both BI-RADS and the machine learning model. Conclusion The ensemble model integrating BI-RADS and machine learning improved lesion classification. Supplementary Information The online version contains supplementary material available at 10.1186/s12880-025-01930-8. Keywords Breast MRI Breast cancer Artificial intelligence Machine learning Binary classification Ministry of Education, Culture, Sports, Science and Technology JP22491733 Matsuda Takuya pmc-status-qastatus 0 pmc-status-live yes pmc-status-embargo no pmc-status-released yes pmc-prop-open-access yes pmc-prop-olf no pmc-prop-manuscript no pmc-prop-legally-suppressed no pmc-prop-has-pdf yes pmc-prop-has-supplement yes pmc-prop-pdf-only no pmc-prop-suppress-copyright no pmc-prop-is-real-version no pmc-prop-is-scanned-article no pmc-prop-preprint no pmc-prop-in-epmc yes issue-copyright-statement © BioMed Central Ltd., part of Springer Nature 2025 Background Breast cancer is the most common cancer among women and the fourth leading cause of cancer-related death among women in Japan [ 1 2 3 A well-documented limitation of BI-RADS-MRI is the subjectivity of its criteria, particularly in category 4, which encompasses lesions with a broad range of malignant potential (> 2% but < 95%) [ 2 4 Quantitative value maps, such as T1 and T2 relaxation times, can be obtained using MRI. Previous studies have reported that these quantitative values aid in differentiating benign from malignant breast lesions [ 5 6 “SyMRI” (SyntheticMR, Linköping, Sweden) which is one of synthetic MRI techniques enable simultaneous acquisition of quantitative T1, T2, and proton density (PD) maps from a single sequence. In this application, images are acquired using a two-dimensional fast spin echo (2D FSE) multi-dynamic, multi-echo (MDME) sequence that collects eight complex-valued images per slice with four saturation delays and two echo times (Fig. 1 7 8 9 Radiomics is an advanced imaging analysis method that extracts numerous features, including morphology, histogram, and texture characteristics, from clinical images, enhancing diagnostic accuracy by identifying key imaging biomarkers [ 10 11 12 13 15 Hwang et al. evaluated the ability of a logistic regression model incorporating radiomics features derived from synthetic MRI to predict pathologic complete response to NAC in 181 participants with triple-negative breast cancer (TNBC). Their findings suggested that quantitative maps obtained from synthetic MRI-based radiomics features, particularly when acquired at mid-treatment, may be useful for identifying early NAC responders in TNBC [ 16 The purpose of this study was to investigate the diagnostic accuracy of machine learning models incorporating radiomics features extracted from synthetic MRI images of the breast, both before and after contrast enhancement, to differentiate between benign and malignant breast mass lesions. Methods Clinical data This study was approved by the institutional review board of the author’s hospital. Patients who underwent contrast-enhanced breast MRI with a protocol including an MDME sequence on a 3.0 T MRI scanner (SIGNA Architect, GE HealthCare, Milwaukee, WI) between February 2018 and August 2022 were retrospectively included. A histopathological diagnosis obtained via biopsy or surgery was considered the gold standard for lesion classification as benign or malignant. The inclusion criteria consisted of patients who underwent breast MRI with pre- and post-contrast MDME sequences. Patients were excluded if (1) no breast lesion in breast MRI was identified, (2) only non-mass lesions were present, (3) the lesion was too small to be detected on quantitative value maps, (4) the histopathological diagnosis was inconclusive regarding malignancy, or (5) NAC had been administered before MRI. Patients were divided into training and test cohorts. The test cohort consisted of a temporally independent consecutive case series. In the training cohort, if multiple masses were present in a single patient, only the largest mass per patient was included. In the test cohort, if multiple masses were present in a single case, the largest mass per breast was included. MRI imaging protocols and quantitative image analysis Breast MRI was performed using a 3.0 T system (SIGNA Architect, GE HealthCare, Milwaukee, WI) with an eight-channel phased-array breast surface coil. All patients were scanned in the prone position. The imaging sequences included in this study are shown in Fig. 2 17 18  Fig. 1 Schematic overview of synthetic MRI. Complex-valued images were acquired using four saturation delays and two echo times. Post-processing was performed using the dedicated commercial application SyMRI NEURO to generate quantitative T1, T2, and proton density (PD) maps Fig. 2 The MRI protocol of this study. MDME; multi-dynamic multi-echo, DWI: diffusion-weighted imaging, DCE-MRI: dynamic contrast-enhanced MRI The DCE-MRI acquisitions were performed using a T1-weighted 3D fast spoiled gradient-recalled echo sequence with parallel volume imaging for breast assessment (Volume Imaged Breast Assessment [VIBRANT], GE HealthCare). The DCE-MRI sequence parameters were as follows: TR, 7.2 ms; TE, 2.4 ms; flip angle, 10°; FOV, 350 × 329 mm; number of slices, 224; slice thickness, 1.4 mm; and acquisition matrix, 350 × 256. Following an intravenous injection of a gadolinium-based contrast agent at a rate of 2 mL/s and a dose of 0.2 mmol/kg, six post-contrast dynamic scans were acquired. The first post-contrast sequence was acquired 60 s after contrast injection, with the subsequent five series acquired at 60-s intervals. Quantitative T1 and T2 relaxation time maps (Q-maps) were obtained from MDME sequence images. A T1/T2 ratio map was created by calculating the pixel-wise ratio of T1 and T2 values. As both T1 and T2 maps were generated from a single MDME pulse sequence, no misregistration occurred between them, enabling precise pixel-based ratio calculations. Lesion segmentation on synthetic MRI The local extent of lesion boundaries on synthetic MRI was unclear, making precise annotation challenging (Additional file 1 A board-certified radiologist identified the lesion on all datasets using the resliced DCE-MRI images and manually delineated the visible lesion boundary on all slices containing the lesion using 3D segmentation tools in Insight Toolkit-SNAP (ITK-SNAP) software [ 19 Image registration As the scans were performed at two different time points (before and after contrast injection), patient motion may have occurred. This motion resulted in misregistration between DCE-MRI and MDME images. To correct this misalignment, 3D co-registration was performed between the DCE-MRI and MDME image volumes (Additional file 2 20 Feature extraction and analysis The feature extraction process in this study is summarized in Fig. 3  Fig. 3 Summary of the feature extraction process. Clinical features, lesion shape features, and textural evaluation metrics were extracted from electronic medical records and MRI images Clinical features Clinical features included age, menopausal status, and presence or absence of symptoms, extracted from electronic medical records at the time of breast MRI. Lesion shape features Fourteen morphological shape features were extracted from the lesion boundary on DCE-MRI, as annotated by a radiologist. The boundary was smoothed and inflated using binary dilation with a 3 × 3 kernel mask. Radiomics features extraction of T1/T2 A radiomics feature mapping framework [ 21 \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
