eement between two radiologists was assessed using the weighted Cohen’s Kappa coefficient. The AUCs of BI-RADS-MRI, the machine learning model, and the ensemble method were compared using the DeLong test with Bonferroni correction (three comparisons). A significance level of p Computer environment Machine learning was conducted on Ubuntu 20.04 Long-Term Support using an Intel Xeon Silver 4108 CPU (8 cores, 1.80 GHz) and an NVIDIA Quadro Ray Tracing Texel eXtreme (RTX) 5000 Graphics Processing Unit. Results Dataset split A total of 471 patients who underwent breast MRI with pre- and post-contrast MDME sequences were included. Patients were excluded based on the following criteria: 44 patients in whom no enhanced lesion in breast MRI was detected, 92 patients with non-mass lesions, 12 patients with small lesions, 33 patients with unclear benign or malignant status in histopathological diagnosis, and 51 patients who received NAC before MRI. After excluding 232 patients, the final dataset comprised 199 lesions (48 benign, 151 malignant) from 199 patients for cross-validation and 43 lesions (15 benign, 28 malignant) from 40 patients for testing. Subtype details are provided in Additional files 3 4 Inter-annotator agreement The mean Dice coefficients for the two radiologists were 0.845 ± 0.086 (95% Confidence Interval (CI), 0.813–0.878) with inflation and 0.783 ± 0.116 (95% CI, 0.740–0.827) without inflation. Dice scores with inflation were significantly higher than those without inflation ( p BI-RADS-MRI The weighted Cohen’s Kappa coefficient for BI-RADS category agreement between the two radiologists was 0.853 (95% CI, 0.796–0.911), indicating strong interobserver agreement. In the final BI-RADS assessment categories, the cross-validation dataset contained 17 lesions in category 3 (17 benign), 119 in category 4 (30 benign, 89 malignant), and 63 in category 5 (1 benign, 62 malignant). For the cross-validation dataset, BI-RADS achieved sensitivity, specificity, accuracy, and AUC value of 100% (95% CI, 97.6–100.0), 35.4% (95% CI, 22.2–50.5), 84.4% (95% CI,78.6–89.2), and 0.677 (95% CI, 0.609–0.745), respectively. Accuracy by category was 100% for category 3, 74.8% (95% CI, 66.0–82.3) for category 4, and 98.4% (95% CI, 91.5–100.0) for category 5. The test dataset contained 5 lesions in category 3 (5 benign), 29 in category 4 (10 benign, 19 malignant), and 9 in category 5 (9 malignant). For the test dataset, BI-RADS achieved sensitivity, specificity, accuracy, and AUC value of 100% (95% CI, 87.6–100.0), 33.3% (95% CI, 11.8–61.6), 76.7% (95% CI, 61.4–88.2), and 0.667 (95% CI, 0.543–0.790), respectively. Accuracy was 100% for categories 3 and 5, and 65.5% (95% CI, 45.7–82.0) for category 4. Machine learning models The average diagnostic performance of each machine learning model on the stratified five-fold cross-validation dataset is shown in Table 2 On the test dataset, LR achieved sensitivity, specificity, accuracy, and AUC value of 64.3% (95% CI, 44.1–81.4), 80.0% (95% CI, 51.9–95.7), 69.8% (95% CI, 53.9–82.8), and 0.707 (95% CI, 0.535–0.879), respectively. On the subset of BI-RADS category 3 (all benign), LR achieved accuracy of 80.0% (95% CI, 28.4–99.5). On the subset of BI-RADS category 4, LR achieved sensitivity, specificity, accuracy, and AUC value of 73.7% (95% CI, 48.8–90.9), 80.0% (95% CI, 44.4–97.5), 75.9% (95% CI, 56.6–89.7), and 0.695 (95% CI, 0.477–0.912), respectively. On the subset of BI-RADS category 5 (all malignant), LR achieved accuracy of 44.4% (95% CI, 13.7–78.8). The importance and impact of eight selected features were analyzed, and results are shown in two summary plots (Fig. 4 \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
