 27 28 p 29 27 Previous studies indicate that visual support from additional images (e.g., post-contrast T1-weighted images) is necessary for radiomics feature extraction, as lesion contours are often unclear in quantitative value maps [ 16 BI-RADS-MRI categorization is widely used for assessing benign and malignant breast masses in clinical settings [ 2 3 2 30 31 32 BI-RADS-MRI categorization demonstrates high sensitivity but variable specificity for breast cancer [ 4 4 Previous research suggests that incorporating manually measured quantitative values from synthetic MRI alongside DCE-MRI evaluation improves diagnostic performance for BI-RADS-MRI category 4 lesions [ 33 The ensemble algorithm combining BI-RADS-MRI and machine learning with radiomics features from weighted images achieves high diagnostic performance by reclassifying BI-RADS-MRI category 4 lesions [ 34 35 34 35 In this study, we reduced the number of features using the VIF and the Boruta algorithm. Among the retained features, those identified as important in the LR model included menopausal status, minor axis length, age, and select TEMs. The finding that age is a key feature aligns with statistical data indicating that breast cancer incidence varies by age [ 1 This study has some limitations. First, it is a single-institution, single-vendor observational study. Previous research in head MRI demonstrated high reproducibility of quantitative values using synthetic MRI across different MRI vendors [ 36 37 Conclusions We evaluated machine learning models utilizing radiomics features from synthetic MRI-derived quantitative value maps for differentiating benign and malignant breast masses. Our findings suggest that diagnostic performance improves when an ensemble algorithm integrating BI-RADS-MRI and machine learning is applied. Supplementary Information Below is the link to the electronic supplementary material.  Supplementary Material 1  Supplementary Material 2  Supplementary Material 3  Supplementary